00:21:20.620 --> 00:21:23.410
professor of behavior economics,
and the author of the book

00:21:23.410 --> 00:21:27.130
"Predictably Irrational."

00:21:27.130 --> 00:21:29.410
So I'd like to frame
this presentation

00:21:29.410 --> 00:21:31.372
around this framework
that you have developed

00:21:31.372 --> 00:21:32.830
at the lab that
could help you make

00:21:32.830 --> 00:21:34.640
better decisions in your app.

00:21:34.640 --> 00:21:37.300
So first of all, think
about the behavior.

00:21:37.300 --> 00:21:40.750
What's the exact behavior that
you want your user to achieve?

00:21:40.750 --> 00:21:43.330
Then think about the barriers.

00:21:43.330 --> 00:21:46.180
What are the elements that
could prevent your user

00:21:46.180 --> 00:21:48.290
from achieving this behavior?

00:21:48.290 --> 00:21:50.500
And finally, think
about the benefits.

00:21:50.500 --> 00:21:54.230
What do I gain once I
achieve that behavior?

00:21:54.230 --> 00:21:56.896
So let's quickly jump
into one example.

00:21:56.896 --> 00:21:58.270
This is the first
screen that you

00:21:58.270 --> 00:22:00.490
used to get when
you opened Fabulous.

00:22:00.490 --> 00:22:03.680
And as you can see,
it looks pretty good.

00:22:03.680 --> 00:22:04.540
Let's get Fabulous.

00:22:04.540 --> 00:22:06.581
What's your most important
health goal right now?

00:22:06.581 --> 00:22:09.400
Then you can choose to feel
more energized, to sleep better.

00:22:09.400 --> 00:22:10.510
Looks pretty well.

00:22:10.510 --> 00:22:14.500
But there is one big
problem with this screen.

00:22:14.500 --> 00:22:19.000
I'll give you just a few
seconds to think it out.

00:22:19.000 --> 00:22:22.450
So the problem with the
screen was the question

00:22:22.450 --> 00:22:24.010
that we were asking.

00:22:24.010 --> 00:22:26.500
What's your most important
health goal right now?

00:22:26.500 --> 00:22:29.410
So when users read this, they
started asking themselves

00:22:29.410 --> 00:22:31.090
all sorts of questions.

00:22:31.090 --> 00:22:33.160
Can I make the wrong choice?

00:22:33.160 --> 00:22:34.940
Can I change my opinion later?

00:22:34.940 --> 00:22:37.090
What if I want to
change my goal?

00:22:37.090 --> 00:22:41.170
So one simple change that
we did is just asking them

00:22:41.170 --> 00:22:43.300
which goal would you
like to start with.

00:22:43.300 --> 00:22:45.670
And now, we are giving
them the permission

00:22:45.670 --> 00:22:47.780
to change their minds later.

00:22:47.780 --> 00:22:51.010
And this has uplifted the
onboarding completion rate

00:22:51.010 --> 00:22:52.250
by 15%.

00:22:52.250 --> 00:22:54.670
So we wanted to go
even further than this,

00:22:54.670 --> 00:22:56.530
and we started limiting
the options as well,

00:22:56.530 --> 00:22:59.350
like providing them
with a default option.

00:22:59.350 --> 00:23:03.460
And this again has increased
the retention on day one.

00:23:03.460 --> 00:23:05.050
So here's a tip.

00:23:05.050 --> 00:23:07.360
Your user is using
your app, and he's

00:23:07.360 --> 00:23:10.450
asking himself all sorts
of questions all the time.

00:23:10.450 --> 00:23:12.280
Can I put my credit
card information?

00:23:12.280 --> 00:23:13.690
Is it secure enough?

00:23:13.690 --> 00:23:16.770
So try to answer all these
questions for the user.

00:23:16.770 --> 00:23:19.420
Try always to provide the
answer, so that the user

00:23:19.420 --> 00:23:20.770
doesn't feel frustrated.

00:23:20.770 --> 00:23:22.990
Because otherwise, if
he starts asking himself

00:23:22.990 --> 00:23:25.510
too many questions, he
will just close the app.

00:23:28.050 --> 00:23:30.220
So to tell you a little
bit about Fabulous.

00:23:30.220 --> 00:23:33.710
In Fabulous, we aim to help
you build a morning routine.

00:23:33.710 --> 00:23:36.320
And in our opinion, this
is a good morning routine.

00:23:36.320 --> 00:23:37.250
You wake up.

00:23:37.250 --> 00:23:38.420
You drink water.

00:23:38.420 --> 00:23:40.930
You exercise a little bit,
and then for some people,

00:23:40.930 --> 00:23:43.640
you would eat a great breakfast.

00:23:43.640 --> 00:23:47.004
In order to get you to do this,
this is how we used to do it.

00:23:47.004 --> 00:23:48.170
This was the old onboarding.

00:23:48.170 --> 00:23:49.730
So you would get
to the screen where

00:23:49.730 --> 00:23:51.680
you have all these
habits, and then

00:23:51.680 --> 00:23:53.630
everything else is
in and out, and you

00:23:53.630 --> 00:23:55.940
need to tap on Drink Water.

00:23:55.940 --> 00:23:58.550
So we were forcing
the users to do this.

00:23:58.550 --> 00:24:01.640
And I have to tell
you, they were really

00:24:01.640 --> 00:24:03.150
frustrated about this.

00:24:03.150 --> 00:24:05.030
They thought that we
were forcing them.

00:24:05.030 --> 00:24:07.670
They even sent us
this kind of email.

00:24:07.670 --> 00:24:12.950
You betrayed my trust when I
had great expectations for you.

00:24:12.950 --> 00:24:16.290
Well, how can we solve this?

00:24:16.290 --> 00:24:20.010
Let's go back to these
ideas of behavior economics.

00:24:20.010 --> 00:24:22.220
Let's first start
with the behavior.

00:24:22.220 --> 00:24:24.590
What's the behavior that
you are trying to achieve?

00:24:24.590 --> 00:24:28.770
Feeling more energized--
well, that's not the behavior,

00:24:28.770 --> 00:24:29.270
actually.

00:24:29.270 --> 00:24:30.830
That's the outcome.

00:24:30.830 --> 00:24:33.000
If you want to think
about the behavior,

00:24:33.000 --> 00:24:36.860
think about the exact steps
that your user needs to take.

00:24:36.860 --> 00:24:39.620
In our case, it's waking
up in the morning,

00:24:39.620 --> 00:24:41.420
reaching out to my
bottle of water,

00:24:41.420 --> 00:24:44.870
and then drinking water, and
taking some time to feel great.

00:24:44.870 --> 00:24:48.680
The behavior is not the outcome.

00:24:48.680 --> 00:24:52.070
And then let's get to the
second step, the barriers.

00:24:52.070 --> 00:24:54.530
I want to drink water,
or I don't want.

00:24:54.530 --> 00:24:56.130
What are the barriers?

00:24:56.130 --> 00:24:58.080
So we conducted a user survey.

00:24:58.080 --> 00:25:00.920
And these were the
three main obstacles.

00:25:00.920 --> 00:25:04.350
I'm not convinced that
I need to drink water.

00:25:04.350 --> 00:25:07.430
I want to drink water, but
I don't have water at reach.

00:25:07.430 --> 00:25:12.060
Or I'm just not very committed.

00:25:12.060 --> 00:25:13.800
Let's try to solve this.

00:25:13.800 --> 00:25:15.100
This is the new onboarding.

00:25:15.100 --> 00:25:17.910
The new onboarding, instead
of asking you to drink water,

00:25:17.910 --> 00:25:19.900
we start by asking
you a few questions.

00:25:19.900 --> 00:25:22.560
Do you want to build a habit
of exercising in the morning?

00:25:22.560 --> 00:25:23.760
Some people might say yes.

00:25:23.760 --> 00:25:25.240
Some people might say no.

00:25:25.240 --> 00:25:27.419
Then, do you want to
build the habit of eating

00:25:27.419 --> 00:25:28.710
great breakfast in the morning?

00:25:28.710 --> 00:25:30.030
Same, some people might say yes.

00:25:30.030 --> 00:25:31.071
Some people might say no.

00:25:31.071 --> 00:25:33.900
And then we ask you the most
important question for us.

00:25:33.900 --> 00:25:35.730
Do you want to drink
water in the morning?

00:25:35.730 --> 00:25:38.930
So this seems very easy related
to the three other goals.

00:25:38.930 --> 00:25:40.120
It's just drinking water.

00:25:40.120 --> 00:25:42.720
So even if I said no to
the two other questions,

00:25:42.720 --> 00:25:43.710
I'm going to say yes.

00:25:43.710 --> 00:25:45.480
Almost 99% of the
people are going

00:25:45.480 --> 00:25:47.970
to say yes, I want to
drink water in the morning.

00:25:47.970 --> 00:25:50.840
And in this case, it was
your choice, actually.

00:25:50.840 --> 00:25:52.530
It was something that
you choose to do.

00:25:52.530 --> 00:25:56.240
It's not us forcing this on you.

00:25:56.240 --> 00:25:59.470
Now, let's think about
the second barrier.

00:25:59.470 --> 00:26:01.370
I'm not very committed.

00:26:01.370 --> 00:26:03.110
I don't feel very
committed to this.

00:26:03.110 --> 00:26:04.940
Well, what you can
do in this case

00:26:04.940 --> 00:26:08.120
is using what we call in
behavior clinics implementation

00:26:08.120 --> 00:26:11.130
intention, which is
simply asking the user.

00:26:11.130 --> 00:26:14.390
Do you commit to
drink water tomorrow?

00:26:14.390 --> 00:26:16.520
And you can even
enhance this effect

00:26:16.520 --> 00:26:18.920
by using what we
call active choice.

00:26:18.920 --> 00:26:20.600
Active choice means
that you're going

00:26:20.600 --> 00:26:23.570
to reframe the yes question
as something very positive

00:26:23.570 --> 00:26:24.740
for your user, like--

00:26:24.740 --> 00:26:27.560
I want to drink water and
feel great about myself.

00:26:27.560 --> 00:26:29.920
And then you frame the
negative answer as something

00:26:29.920 --> 00:26:31.250
not that good.

00:26:31.250 --> 00:26:33.120
I don't want to drink water.

00:26:33.120 --> 00:26:34.940
I don't care about my health.

00:26:34.940 --> 00:26:39.230
So here's another way in
which you can do this.

00:26:39.230 --> 00:26:41.210
As you know, we're all
trying to get our users

00:26:41.210 --> 00:26:42.830
to invite their friends.

00:26:42.830 --> 00:26:44.570
And generally, we
would ask them.

00:26:44.570 --> 00:26:46.700
Please invite your
friends to our app.

00:26:46.700 --> 00:26:48.155
That's something really great.

00:26:48.155 --> 00:26:49.900
It will make us happy.

00:26:49.900 --> 00:26:52.680
But generally, users
will just turn away.

00:26:52.680 --> 00:26:55.610
So another way of doing
this is, first of all,

00:26:55.610 --> 00:26:58.036
by stating the benefits.

00:26:58.036 --> 00:26:59.660
If you invite your
friends to Fabulous,

00:26:59.660 --> 00:27:02.270
you are much more likely
to complete your habits.

00:27:02.270 --> 00:27:04.970
And then second of all,
let's use the active choice.

00:27:04.970 --> 00:27:07.090
So here we provide them
with three choices.

00:27:07.090 --> 00:27:08.240
Two of them are positive.

00:27:08.240 --> 00:27:09.380
One is negative.

00:27:09.380 --> 00:27:10.160
One of them is--

00:27:10.160 --> 00:27:13.340
I'd like to invite my friend
to join me on this journey.

00:27:13.340 --> 00:27:16.370
I want to invite my friend to
monitor me on this journey.

00:27:16.370 --> 00:27:18.070
And then the third choice is--

00:27:18.070 --> 00:27:19.505
I'll do it on my own.

00:27:19.505 --> 00:27:21.820
It's a little bit
negative, actually.

00:27:21.820 --> 00:27:25.790
So always answer this
question for the user.

00:27:25.790 --> 00:27:27.170
What is in it for me?

00:27:27.170 --> 00:27:29.510
What do I gain out
of doing this action?

00:27:29.510 --> 00:27:30.980
Always provide the benefits.

00:27:30.980 --> 00:27:33.890
Go through the copy of your
app, and state everything

00:27:33.890 --> 00:27:36.920
as benefits, not as goals,
not as objectives, but as

00:27:36.920 --> 00:27:39.530
benefits for the final user.

00:27:39.530 --> 00:27:42.050
Now, here's a bonus one.

00:27:42.050 --> 00:27:44.120
You can get your user
to commit even more

00:27:44.120 --> 00:27:46.700
by using what we call a
commitment contract, which

00:27:46.700 --> 00:27:50.780
is simply asking the
user to commit to a place

00:27:50.780 --> 00:27:53.210
and time in which they are
more likely to accomplish

00:27:53.210 --> 00:27:53.930
that behavior.

00:27:53.930 --> 00:27:56.340
And then you would ask them
to sign up with their name.

00:27:56.340 --> 00:27:58.890
This is called the
commitment contract.

00:27:58.890 --> 00:28:02.000
Now, let's think about
the next barrier.

00:28:02.000 --> 00:28:03.950
Well, I want to drink
water, but I just

00:28:03.950 --> 00:28:06.590
don't have water at reach.

00:28:06.590 --> 00:28:08.420
If you think about
your users, they

00:28:08.420 --> 00:28:11.540
are much more likely
to commit to your app

00:28:11.540 --> 00:28:14.070
when they first opened the
app or when they have just

00:28:14.070 --> 00:28:15.810
completed one milestone.

00:28:15.810 --> 00:28:17.750
So this is the best
time for you to ask

00:28:17.750 --> 00:28:19.460
for even more engagement.

00:28:19.460 --> 00:28:22.760
In our case, after they commit,
we're going to ask them--

00:28:22.760 --> 00:28:25.910
would you like us to
send a reminder tonight

00:28:25.910 --> 00:28:28.640
so that you put your water
bottle by your bedside?

00:28:28.640 --> 00:28:30.420
This is beneficial
for the users.

00:28:30.420 --> 00:28:33.320
So they are really
likely to say yes.

00:28:33.320 --> 00:28:36.380
If you are a finance app,
this could be the right moment

00:28:36.380 --> 00:28:38.840
to ask them to set
up automatic saving.

00:28:38.840 --> 00:28:41.060
If you are Google Photo,
this is the right time

00:28:41.060 --> 00:28:43.700
to ask for auto backup
of your pictures.

00:28:43.700 --> 00:28:46.700
So think about one
action in your app

00:28:46.700 --> 00:28:50.090
that could really lead
to much more engagement.

00:28:50.090 --> 00:28:52.310
Think about ways to
make it automated,

00:28:52.310 --> 00:28:55.610
and then ask the user to
commit to this on high points,

00:28:55.610 --> 00:28:58.640
either on the onboarding or
just after they successfully

00:28:58.640 --> 00:29:01.830
completed the milestone
within your app.

00:29:01.830 --> 00:29:05.240
So now lets get to the third
part, the benefits part.

00:29:05.240 --> 00:29:08.000
What do I gain out
of doing all of this?

00:29:08.000 --> 00:29:11.190
Well, this is an interesting
one, because, of course,

00:29:11.190 --> 00:29:12.870
it's changing from
one app to the next.

00:29:12.870 --> 00:29:18.800
If you are a weight loss app,
it's very easy for the user

00:29:18.800 --> 00:29:20.660
to know that they
have gained something.

00:29:20.660 --> 00:29:22.820
They will just weigh
themselves one week in,

00:29:22.820 --> 00:29:25.520
and they would see if this
has been beneficial or no.

00:29:25.520 --> 00:29:28.130
So in the case of Fabulous,
since we didn't have that,

00:29:28.130 --> 00:29:29.510
we thought about this idea.

00:29:29.510 --> 00:29:31.410
So each time that you
complete your habits,

00:29:31.410 --> 00:29:34.250
we are going to ask you to
take some time to celebrate,

00:29:34.250 --> 00:29:36.690
to feel good about yourself.

00:29:36.690 --> 00:29:40.010
You need something tangible
to provide for the user

00:29:40.010 --> 00:29:42.140
after a few days of
usage so that they

00:29:42.140 --> 00:29:46.730
understand that they are gaining
something out of your app.

00:29:46.730 --> 00:29:49.220
And here is a good
way to think about it.

00:29:49.220 --> 00:29:50.840
Let's suppose that
they keep using

00:29:50.840 --> 00:29:52.850
your app for a few months.

00:29:52.850 --> 00:29:54.980
How's this going to
transform my life?

00:29:54.980 --> 00:29:57.590
Now, take all these
benefits and make

00:29:57.590 --> 00:30:00.010
them immediate and salient.

00:30:00.010 --> 00:30:02.090
Tell the user-- this
is what you are gaining

00:30:02.090 --> 00:30:05.410
on every step of the way.

00:30:05.410 --> 00:30:06.650
So here it is.

00:30:06.650 --> 00:30:10.550
We have now applied the three
tenets of behavior economics.

00:30:10.550 --> 00:30:12.590
First of all, we started
with the outcome.

00:30:12.590 --> 00:30:14.870
We want the user to
feel more energized,

00:30:14.870 --> 00:30:18.470
and from there, we got the exact
behavior that we need to apply.

00:30:18.470 --> 00:30:22.550
I want to wake up and reach
out to my bottle of water.

00:30:22.550 --> 00:30:24.920
And then we conducted
a user survey

00:30:24.920 --> 00:30:26.480
to know about the barriers.

00:30:26.480 --> 00:30:29.450
And some people are
not committed enough.

00:30:29.450 --> 00:30:31.940
In this case, we used what
we call the implementation

00:30:31.940 --> 00:30:34.130
intention in order to
get them to commit.

00:30:34.130 --> 00:30:36.140
Some people didn't
have water at reach.

00:30:36.140 --> 00:30:39.130
So we used the
active choice idea

00:30:39.130 --> 00:30:42.470
in order to get us to send
them a gentle reminder

00:30:42.470 --> 00:30:44.510
that same night for
them to put a water

00:30:44.510 --> 00:30:46.640
bottle by their bedside.

00:30:46.640 --> 00:30:49.850
And then we have provided
them with a tangible benefit

00:30:49.850 --> 00:30:52.640
by asking them to
celebrate for a few minutes

00:30:52.640 --> 00:30:53.930
their achievements.

00:30:53.930 --> 00:30:55.420
Hope this has been useful.

00:30:55.420 --> 00:30:57.940
Thanks, and back to Jeni.

